Codacy sort of hints at the problem here, which is that you need to add some braces after your `else` and between the `return` statements, i.e.:
```c
    } else {
        usage();
        return 1;
    }
    return 0;
}
```

Done.  I also did some timing testing on this one.  Turns out that just writing:
```python
def nCr(n, r):
    from math import factorial
    if 0 <= r <= n:
        return factorial(n) // (factorial(r) * factorial(n-r))
    else:
        return 0
```
is usually faster than the more complicated thing that was there before, so I replaced it with the above.  I think the exceptions are when n >> r and n >> 1, in which case the complicated math is faster.  I don't think this should hardly ever occur in GalSim though -- certainly not for Zernike coefficients anyway, which is the only place we currently use this.
